12:27.702 --> 12:31.325
We'll put this on the screen because we want you to be able to write it down if you're one of our note-takers in the room.

12:31.345 --> 12:40.434
But definitionally, something that is true of anger is the natural response to a perceived threat to one's happiness.

12:41.378 --> 12:49.522
And most often, not always, but most often, what determines whether anger is righteous or unrighteous is whose happiness

12:49.794 --> 12:50.655
is threatened.

12:50.735 --> 12:53.820
So let me just give you a little bit of a breakdown.

12:53.940 --> 12:54.802
Two different categories.

12:54.862 --> 12:59.969
Righteous anger is when someone else's happiness is being threatened.

13:00.029 --> 13:04.035
We see this as the kind of anger that Jesus was imbued with.

13:04.256 --> 13:09.323
When you read in the Gospel of Mark, it says that he was angry or he was indignant to his disciples.

13:09.383 --> 13:09.624
Why?

13:09.644 --> 13:13.970
Because they kept the little children from coming to him in the Gospel of John.

13:14.030 --> 13:19.058
You see that he sort of flipping tables and driving out money changers with a whip.

13:19.330 --> 13:22.855
because they had turned the Lord's house of prayer into a dinner robbers.

13:22.895 --> 13:24.899
That made him angry as well.

13:24.999 --> 13:28.244
He was angry not on his own behalf, but on behalf of other people.

13:28.524 --> 13:29.025
See how that works?

13:29.466 --> 13:30.467
That's righteous anger.

13:30.527 --> 13:33.412
I love the way John Stott says it when he's talking about Jesus is anger.

13:33.432 --> 13:38.039
He says Jesus is anger is neither mysterious nor irrational.

13:38.139 --> 13:39.301
It's never unpredictable.

13:39.902 --> 13:46.031
It's always predictable because it is provoked by evil and evil alone.

13:46.852 --> 13:47.954
The wrath of God

13:48.354 --> 13:56.021
It's his steady, unrelenting, unremitting, uncompromising antagonism to evil in all its forms and manifestations.

13:57.002 --> 13:57.463
You see that?

13:57.903 --> 14:07.652
God feels anger himself, and yet his antagonism is always towards the same thing and only that thing.

14:09.314 --> 14:14.118
It's always directed at evil, which is so encouraging, isn't it?

14:14.959 --> 14:18.162
Like God's design for his world was not one where

14:18.466 --> 14:23.491
people would be abused and slandered and manipulated and attacked and hurt even.

14:23.832 --> 14:25.554
That was never a part of his design.

14:25.754 --> 14:27.616
And so what we know is evil's days are numbered.

14:28.156 --> 14:31.740
Like ultimately, Jesus has already dealt the initial blow.

14:32.141 --> 14:34.483
He's taken death out by dying himself.

14:34.924 --> 14:38.047
He's gonna come back and he's gonna finish the job.

14:38.067 --> 14:39.068
That's righteous anger.

14:39.248 --> 14:45.335
Now unrighteous anger is anger that's directed when my happiness is being threatened.

14:45.996 --> 14:48.178
Unrighteous anger is when my happiness

14:48.738 --> 14:49.499
is being threatened.

14:49.519 --> 14:51.220
Now, I want to be really clear.

14:51.280 --> 15:01.190
Some of you have suffered some serious injustices through abuse or assault at the hands of another person.

15:01.250 --> 15:07.376
And you have every right to be angry.

15:07.797 --> 15:09.298
That's not what I'm talking about here.

15:09.879 --> 15:14.563
You need to know that makes God very angry.

15:14.583 --> 15:17.586
And he promises in his word that he will

15:18.114 --> 15:19.076
deal with the wicked.

15:19.096 --> 15:21.522
That's not what we're talking about here.

15:22.263 --> 15:29.600
What we're talking about here is this idea that most people's anger, it orbits not around evil, it orbits around ego.

15:31.464 --> 15:35.954
And what I mean by that is it's why people get defensive.

15:36.290 --> 15:38.832
whenever it says something that they don't like or they disagree with them.

15:38.932 --> 15:42.776
Or it's why we grow hateful because we didn't get the kind of outcome that we actually wanted.

15:42.796 --> 15:48.260
Or we feel bitter because, man, someone, they went against us and then they never apologized for it.

15:48.280 --> 15:53.605
And now we just feel this resentment boiling up and building inside, unrighteous anger.

15:53.965 --> 15:56.307
It always comes to its own defense.

15:56.327 --> 16:01.672
I remember seeing this whenever I was in grade school, in high school, growing up, you would always see two guys.

16:01.712 --> 16:06.276
Like they would kind of get into a fight with one another because one of them encroached on the other one's territory.

16:06.256 --> 16:10.200
hurt that other guy's pride, and they would always do the same thing.

16:10.501 --> 16:18.849
Like, they would bow up in front of each other, and they would lock eyes with one another, and they'd begin to stare each other down.

16:19.230 --> 16:25.256
And then if it was really serious, one of them would take his shirt off, which was always kind of strange, and you knew like, oh my gosh, it's really about to go down.

16:25.276 --> 16:26.297
He just took his shirt off, man.

16:26.518 --> 16:29.481
And then the reality is, which we were joking earlier, that would not work today.

16:29.501 --> 16:31.403
You know, it would be like, please put your clothes back on.

16:31.423 --> 16:32.784
Like, I'm not intimidated in the slightest.

16:32.904 --> 16:33.906
Please don't do that any longer.

16:34.166 --> 16:36.228
But at that time, it told us, it was like, man, this is correct.

16:36.208 --> 16:38.791
They're really upset.

16:38.811 --> 16:40.112
They're really angry.

16:40.193 --> 16:40.453
Why?

16:40.713 --> 16:42.735
Because someone has threatened their happiness.

16:43.817 --> 16:45.318
Happiness in their reputation.

16:45.679 --> 16:47.181
Happiness in their pride.

16:47.441 --> 16:48.943
Happiness in their comfort.

16:49.123 --> 16:52.487
And because no one else was going to do anything about it, they had to do something about it.

16:53.288 --> 16:55.250
That's unrighteous anger.

16:55.410 --> 16:57.673
And listen, we don't do this, do we?

16:59.214 --> 16:59.995
Of course we do.

17:00.035 --> 17:06.002
Now you may not puff up and bow up on somebody, but you do possibly mutter under your breath.

17:07.138 --> 17:09.520
or you do nurse a grudge.

17:10.401 --> 17:19.751
Some of you, you indulge revenge fantasies because you might not be able to get back out of them, but you know how you would get back out of them and you love to go to that dark kind of place.

17:19.811 --> 17:20.491
Maybe that's not the case.

17:20.532 --> 17:23.475
Maybe you just sulk.

17:23.495 --> 17:25.056
Like you just find, you know what?

17:25.396 --> 17:27.338
I'm not gonna be able to express this verbally.

17:27.378 --> 17:32.664
I'm gonna just embody this physically and I'm going to feel really down and despondent in my own spirit.

17:32.684 --> 17:34.866
I don't know what it is for you, but here's the thing.

17:36.770 --> 17:42.416
Anger can be dangerous if not expressed effectively.

17:44.398 --> 17:45.179
It's fascinating.

17:46.500 --> 17:49.964
Anger is an emotional response to some threat against your happiness.

17:51.526 --> 17:55.630
But the irony is, anger itself can be the threat to your happiness.

17:57.312 --> 18:03.058
The American Psychological Association says, ineffectively processing anger can lead to

18:03.426 --> 18:14.777
hypertension, high blood pressure, depression, anxiety, as well as a suite of other mental health disruptions, meaning it literally can impair your happiness.

18:16.298 --> 18:17.439
So what are we supposed to do about that?

18:18.640 --> 18:25.627
Well, psychology today, they said this in an article on the topic of anger, and I thought it was so good, I just wanted to read it to you.

18:25.667 --> 18:32.914
They said, unleashing your anger does not produce the sense of catharsis that people crave.

18:33.122 --> 18:35.205
which just tells us that venting is a myth.

18:35.906 --> 18:39.792
Venting is actually not helping you whatsoever, neither is gossiping, it's only hurting you.

18:40.112 --> 18:42.917
It does not produce the sense of catharsis that people crave.

18:43.457 --> 18:45.781
It tends to feed on itself instead.

18:45.821 --> 18:51.469
The best path forward isn't to unleash your anger, it's to understand your anger.

18:52.130 --> 18:57.458
It's roots, it's triggers, it's consequences, and then cultivate the ability

18:57.666 --> 18:58.348
to manage it.

18:58.489 --> 18:59.111
I love that.

18:59.131 --> 19:02.180
I love that it says cultivate the ability to manage it.

19:02.220 --> 19:05.350
It's like a farmer who cultivates a field.

19:05.390 --> 19:09.042
You know, that's what you're supposed to do with all those negative

19:09.090 --> 19:12.594
those feelings inside, those feelings rooted in the core emotion of anger.

19:12.614 --> 19:23.628
Like you're supposed to teal up the soil and pull all the weeds and remove all the rocks and lay down some seed and carefully water so that you grow something good in its place.

19:23.648 --> 19:26.010
And that's everything that David wants to talk to us about in Psalm 37.

19:26.071 --> 19:38.866
He wants to teach you, hey, instead of growing your anger, let's grow something better instead because although your problem may be anger, your perspective, God's perspective.

19:39.362 --> 19:40.203
could be gratitude.

19:41.284 --> 19:43.727
It could be gratitude.

19:45.649 --> 19:58.184
You see, what we need to know as we think about gratitude in God is that the anger is a response to some threat to our happiness.

19:58.244 --> 20:01.267
What if we put our happiness in some place it cannot be threatened?

20:02.489 --> 20:07.154
What if we put it in God who can never be encroached against?

20:07.586 --> 20:11.412
who never at all worries in the face of evil.

20:12.874 --> 20:14.476
That's what David's prompting us towards.

20:14.857 --> 20:25.453
He wants us to step into a kind of relationship with God where we remember how good he is even in the face of how dark the world may become and how troubling the times may get.

20:26.395 --> 20:31.803
And he tells us as we get into Psalm 37, very specifically, how to do it.

20:31.863 --> 20:35.168
He wants to give us four disciplines for growing gratitude.

20:35.789 --> 20:36.530
So if you take a note,

20:36.802 --> 20:39.164
four disciplines for growing gratitude.

20:40.346 --> 20:46.612
The first one we see in verse one says this, fret not yourself because of evil doers.

20:47.233 --> 20:53.159
Be not envious of wrongdoers, for they will soon fade like the grass and wither like the green herb.

20:53.179 --> 21:04.210
We need to stop and we need to talk because what we need to know is what this word fret actually means because we're gonna get into this and what you're gonna see is all of the disciplines, they very quickly come.

21:04.578 --> 21:07.683
And yet before any of them do, David just gives one command.

21:07.723 --> 21:10.307
He says, hey, do not fret yourself.

21:10.427 --> 21:12.971
So we need to ask ourselves, then what does it mean to fret?

21:12.991 --> 21:14.774
Because we don't actually use that kind of language.

21:14.794 --> 21:18.900
Nobody is looking at their friend at the end of a hard day and saying, do not fret, my friend.

21:19.181 --> 21:20.122
No one says that.

21:20.162 --> 21:21.384
So what does David actually mean?

21:21.664 --> 21:28.315
What he's saying is he's saying, hey, be on guard against anger.

21:28.555 --> 21:29.356
You see, it's interesting.

21:29.396 --> 21:33.042
The Hebrew primitive root to fret.

21:33.506 --> 21:37.312
is the idea of to glow or to warm.

21:37.392 --> 21:42.080
And when you take that idea and you morph it into a verb, it means to get heated.

21:45.045 --> 21:54.821
Meaning to get angry, to feel something boiling up inside, burning within, kindling in your soul against whatever someone may have said or done.

21:55.042 --> 21:57.445
And we see this all throughout the scripture.

21:57.486 --> 22:00.210
We don't have time to unpack it, but you can go and see.

22:00.322 --> 22:01.964
It happens in Potiphar, right?

22:02.164 --> 22:06.308
He looks and his anger was kindled against Joseph.

22:06.388 --> 22:11.473
You see Samson after he kills 30 men from Eshkalon, he returns home in hot anger.

22:11.553 --> 22:17.959
Like you can see this idea all throughout the scripture because the thought behind anger is it's not just a flip of the switch.

22:18.380 --> 22:24.566
Yes, of course, there's an instigator, something that catalyzes it into reality, but it doesn't stay there.

22:25.086 --> 22:25.727
It grows.

22:26.408 --> 22:27.188
It's like a fire.

22:27.669 --> 22:28.850
It spreads.

22:29.026 --> 22:33.891
And if not stopped, it burns the whole forest of your life down.

22:34.712 --> 22:37.275
And so we have to know then, how do we keep it from growing?

22:37.295 --> 22:40.538
Well, he's gonna tell us you need to grow gratitude.

22:40.899 --> 22:43.181
That's why he says in verse three, and he gives us the first discipline.

22:43.201 --> 22:44.883
He says, he trusts in the Lord.

22:45.364 --> 22:45.824
Do good.

22:46.205 --> 22:48.787
Dwell in the land and befriend faithfulness.

22:49.929 --> 22:54.533
He tells us to trust the Lord, which just feels like good old Christian advice, doesn't it?

22:54.574 --> 22:56.375
Does trust in God?

22:57.036 --> 22:58.738
How the heck am I supposed to do that?

22:58.818 --> 23:01.100
Has anyone ever considered that reality?

23:01.120 --> 23:02.562
Like I read the scriptures like trust and learn.

23:02.582 --> 23:06.846
I'm like, okay, I know I'm supposed to, but I'd like to grow in my capacity to do so.

23:06.886 --> 23:09.369
Can someone help me know how to trust in God?

23:09.569 --> 23:10.810
Well, how do you trust in anybody?

23:11.871 --> 23:14.394
You remember what made them trustworthy to begin with.

23:14.974 --> 23:15.835
That's the thing here.

23:16.115 --> 23:18.918
You remember, that's the first discipline.

23:19.119 --> 23:23.783
If you wanna grow your gratitude, then you need to learn the discipline of remembrance.

23:25.145 --> 23:26.546
And I mean it when I say discipline.

23:27.042 --> 23:29.868
This isn't just something you subconsciously wander your way into.

23:30.169 --> 23:34.217
It's something you should very meticulously apply to your life.

23:34.338 --> 23:40.992
We should learn to discipline ourselves in remembrance, because remembrance is what leads to trust.

23:41.633 --> 23:43.858
So whenever I want Brooke

23:44.002 --> 23:44.623
to trust me.

23:44.723 --> 23:50.889
Whenever it's, hey, she needs me to show up on time, or I need her to trust it, I'll get that thing done, or I need her to trust it.

23:50.909 --> 23:52.551
I'm gonna call those people.

23:53.032 --> 23:57.336
I don't appeal to her trust by saying, but baby, you know, I'm such a good man.

23:57.557 --> 23:58.518
Like, I don't do that.

23:59.319 --> 24:00.420
That's not gonna get me anywhere.

24:00.460 --> 24:04.224
I don't look at her and say, but you know that I mean well, like, that doesn't work either.

24:04.284 --> 24:04.925
What do I say?

24:04.945 --> 24:07.387
Hey, you can trust me.

24:07.467 --> 24:07.668
Why?

24:08.368 --> 24:09.810
Remember when I showed up

24:10.146 --> 24:11.167
all those times before.

24:11.207 --> 24:12.930
Remember what I called all those times before.

24:12.950 --> 24:17.316
Remember what I did, whatever it was you wanted all those times before.

24:17.456 --> 24:23.144
I called back times of previous trustworthiness so she can know she can trust me today.

24:23.164 --> 24:24.165
And here's the reality.

24:24.185 --> 24:28.331
Like I can look at it and be like, hey, remember when and she can look at me and say, but remember when you did it?

24:29.172 --> 24:31.836
The truth of the matter is though, we cannot do that with God.

24:32.537 --> 24:39.506
There was never a moment in our relationship or over the course of all time where God did not keep his word.

24:39.970 --> 24:43.254
did not honor his promise or did not come through in the clutch.

24:43.794 --> 24:48.139
Like when Abraham went to sacrifice his son, God provided an alternative instead.

24:49.000 --> 24:53.385
When God's people cried out from slavery in Egypt, he heard them and he delivered them.

24:53.645 --> 24:59.832
When Ruth had no kinsman, redeemer, or hope to speak of God sent Boaz to give her a family.

25:00.233 --> 25:04.978
When David, he stood toe to toe with Goliath, the God of Israel's armies fought for him.

25:05.314 --> 25:09.078
When Elijah confronted the prophets of Baal, God set fire from heaven.

25:09.239 --> 25:14.405
When Jehoshaphat saw armies invading all around, God heard his prayer and he vanquished his enemies.

25:14.625 --> 25:20.492
And here's the thing, when we were dead in our sins, Christ, our rescuer came running.

25:21.273 --> 25:21.593
Why?

25:22.114 --> 25:24.677
Because God is trustworthy.

25:25.197 --> 25:26.198
He's trustworthy.

25:26.699 --> 25:29.202
We can believe he will keep

25:29.314 --> 25:31.377
His promises, He will honor His Word.

25:31.597 --> 25:33.760
He never fails a commitment.

25:33.820 --> 25:40.868
And when He commits to deliver us out of our sin and bring us back to Himself, we can believe He's going to do it.

25:41.509 --> 25:42.170
He's going to do it.

25:42.671 --> 25:45.054
But we have to cultivate remembrance.

25:45.795 --> 25:47.837
We have really good reason to trust God biblically.

25:48.578 --> 25:53.785
If that wasn't enough reason, then just go read the rest of the book because you'll see it again and again and again.

25:53.905 --> 25:58.130
And yet not only do you have good reason to trust Him biblically, you have good reason to trust Him personally.

25:58.914 --> 26:00.396
And it serves us to remember it.

26:00.776 --> 26:11.988
According to one study, if you spend five minutes a day remembering what you have to be grateful for, that can increase your long-term well-being by upwards of 10% or more.

26:12.649 --> 26:13.410
Just five minutes.

26:14.171 --> 26:19.216
Thinking about what you have to be grateful for, remembering God's goodness in the past.

26:19.236 --> 26:22.339
And so what reasons do you have to trust God?

26:22.460 --> 26:28.466
I don't know what they are for you, but I know what they are in my own life because over the course of my life, I have seen God be so very faithful to me.

26:28.738 --> 26:32.786
And there's three things that stand out as being especially significant.

26:32.946 --> 26:35.711
I can look back and I can trust God because of my salvation.

26:37.335 --> 26:42.965
Like I wasn't looking to get saved at Taco Bell at 11 p.m. at night sitting across the table from a friend in a corner booth.

26:44.128 --> 26:47.474
And yet God, that's exactly what he intended to do that evening.

26:47.842 --> 26:49.044
I didn't go there looking for that.

26:49.084 --> 26:50.787
I don't know what I went there looking for to begin with.

26:50.827 --> 26:51.508
It was Taco Bell.

26:51.548 --> 26:54.353
And yet God knew I needed to find him in that place.

26:54.373 --> 26:58.540
And so I showed up and I sat across the table from my buddy and he just started unpacking for me.

26:58.941 --> 27:02.487
Not just here are some good rules of Christian living to abide by.

27:02.827 --> 27:08.096
He started telling me about the character and the nature of God and his signature across creation.

27:08.336 --> 27:11.702
And as I heard all of it, my curiosity was replaced with desire.

27:11.983 --> 27:14.066
And I wanted what he had given me in that place.

27:14.274 --> 27:16.016
where you're like, I want what you want.

27:16.097 --> 27:16.918
I want what you got.

27:17.018 --> 27:18.219
I want him.

27:18.320 --> 27:19.321
That's where I was at.

27:19.641 --> 27:21.945
And the beauty of it was it didn't come out of me.

27:21.965 --> 27:23.527
It came from God.

27:23.607 --> 27:29.655
He wanted me first and then I wanted him in response.

27:29.675 --> 27:34.142
The second reason I've got good cause to trust in God is I can look at my marriage.

27:34.943 --> 27:43.154
Like I know in my marriage, I was way more immature than I thought when we first said I do.

27:43.938 --> 27:49.204
And as a result, we dealt with some really tough times, many of which were my own fault.

27:49.985 --> 27:56.353
And yet, I can confidently stand before you and I can say, Brooke and I have never been happier in our marriage.

27:56.854 --> 27:59.677
And it's because God is faithful, not because we figured it out.

28:01.259 --> 28:10.610
God was faithful when we messed up, when I continually screwed up, he didn't.

28:11.138 --> 28:15.082
he persisted in his kindness towards me and his patience as well.

28:15.502 --> 28:17.104
And then the third reason is in my job.

28:18.125 --> 28:29.536
Like, I almost gave up on ministry at one point, like a dream that I had for so long etched in the journals from my days in college was snatched away from me.

28:30.678 --> 28:34.582
And yet, though that was my dream, God replaced it with a better dream.

28:34.602 --> 28:36.483
He replaced it with this, with you.

28:37.605 --> 28:39.026
And because he did,

28:39.170 --> 28:40.992
I have good cause to trust him.

28:41.673 --> 28:50.082
I have great reason because I stand here in the joy of my life ministering to young adults in Dallas, Texas and all across the nation.

28:51.123 --> 28:54.847
He has given you really good reason to trust him.

28:55.728 --> 28:57.570
So what reasons has he given you?

28:58.111 --> 29:01.835
And even if you're here and you don't know, Jesus, you have no relationship with God.

29:02.275 --> 29:05.699
Whatever good you have in your life, it's from him.

29:05.759 --> 29:08.562
He's the giver of every good and perfect gift.

29:09.154 --> 29:11.778
And then come as a result of anything other than him.

29:11.818 --> 29:16.605
And so even though you may not have a relationship with him, you can actually recognize him tonight.

29:16.945 --> 29:22.694
You can see it as true from he who only and always gives good.

29:24.296 --> 29:28.082
Psalm 103, one and two says this, praise the Lord my soul.

29:28.102 --> 29:31.567
All my inmost being praises holy name.

29:31.587 --> 29:32.268
I love that.

29:32.949 --> 29:35.533
Say not all my outmost being, because a lot of people do that.

29:35.553 --> 29:39.058
Don't they, they praise externally, but they don't praise internally.

29:40.194 --> 29:40.975
And he's like, not me.

29:41.837 --> 29:43.901
I'm going to praise you for my inmost being.

29:45.724 --> 29:53.118
Praise the Lord, my soul, and forget not all his benefits.

29:54.781 --> 29:59.068
So, friend, let me ask you, what benefits of his have you forgotten?

30:00.671 --> 30:04.338
If you feel like your trust in God

30:04.706 --> 30:07.491
is struggling, your gratitude in God is failing.

30:07.531 --> 30:09.174
What benefits of his have you forgotten?

30:09.194 --> 30:11.057
Have you forgotten the fact that he's given you a new name?

30:12.199 --> 30:14.403
Like do you look back at your past and think that those are the things that define you?

30:14.423 --> 30:15.425
Those are not the things that define you.

30:15.445 --> 30:19.753
The things that define you are the fact that he has called you son or daughter if you place your faith in him.

30:20.975 --> 30:25.303
Like are you sitting here tonight and you've forgotten that he's given you a bright future?

30:25.343 --> 30:29.330
One where he's prepared good works in advance for you to walk into?

30:30.114 --> 30:31.335
Like you're here and you've forgotten.

30:31.356 --> 30:32.957
He's given you a really big family.

30:32.998 --> 30:34.780
You got brothers and sisters all across this room.

30:34.800 --> 30:36.141
I don't care what kind of home you came from.

30:36.161 --> 30:43.270
He's given you a big family full of brothers, sisters, spiritual fathers, spiritual mothers.

30:44.091 --> 30:47.075
And he's gone and he has prepared a place for you in his house.

30:48.036 --> 30:51.680
Have you forgotten that he's given you unconditional love?

30:52.481 --> 30:56.306
No matter how big a mess you've made of your life, how big a mistake

30:56.738 --> 30:59.943
you feel like you are or how deep the stain of your sin actually goes.

31:01.365 --> 31:05.251
Christ loved you when you were already at your worst.

31:06.794 --> 31:10.700
Forget not his benefits because it's in his benefits that we remember.

31:11.361 --> 31:14.346
We have good cause for gratitude.

31:14.406 --> 31:15.167
That's the first one.

31:15.848 --> 31:16.429
Let's keep going.

31:16.449 --> 31:16.810
Verse four.

31:18.352 --> 31:21.898
He says, delight yourself in the Lord and he'll give you the desires of your heart.

31:22.659 --> 31:23.260
I love this.

31:23.320 --> 31:24.562
Notice it doesn't say,

31:24.866 --> 31:26.989
Get the desires of your heart and you'll delight in the Lord.

31:27.810 --> 31:31.976
But just get that job or that bonus or that boyfriend and then what you'll feel is a deep sense of delight.

31:32.336 --> 31:33.518
And God, that's not what he's saying.

31:33.538 --> 31:37.022
What he's saying instead is that when you get God, you get everything.

31:37.844 --> 31:39.886
When you get God, you get everything.

31:40.547 --> 31:46.495
Which is important for us to know because if we want to grow our gratitude, the second discipline you have to learn is the discipline of presence.

31:47.397 --> 31:48.498
The discipline of presence.

31:48.962 --> 31:50.506
What do I mean when I say presence?

31:50.626 --> 31:53.653
Well, what does it mean to be in someone's presence?

31:53.693 --> 32:03.355
It means that you're near to them, like you're encountering the expression of their personality, you're engaging with them face to face.

32:03.435 --> 32:04.999
It means you're close to them.

32:05.099 --> 32:06.482
That's what we're talking about here.

32:07.746 --> 32:18.161
Dating gurus, galore, all herald the importance of being present in a relationship because it creates an environment where your significant other understands just how much they matter to you.

32:18.241 --> 32:24.951
When you're willing to block out all other distractions and focus your attention, they understand that they matter.

32:25.132 --> 32:30.660
They're important because nothing says I love you like silencing your phone, looking in their eyes and listening with your face.

32:31.000 --> 32:35.387
That's ultimately what's going to convince someone that you care about them.

32:35.407 --> 32:37.650
It's that you're present with them.

32:38.242 --> 32:46.336
as just one example, some of you really understand this because you honestly thought about skipping tonight so you could watch the season finale of Dancing with the Stars.

32:46.396 --> 32:47.759
What would you do without recording it?

32:47.779 --> 32:51.625
But the reason why you thought about skipping is because you are just so smitten with Robert Irwin.

32:53.489 --> 33:03.346
Notice the laughter in the room was all female, not because any of them are animal conservationists, but because they think he's cute, they like the way his hips move, and ultimately,

33:03.522 --> 33:06.666
They just want to see how this chapter in his life is going to conclude.

33:06.907 --> 33:09.170
You've spent so much time with him.

33:10.311 --> 33:12.374
And thus you care about him.

33:12.414 --> 33:15.478
You have been present for all of his highs and his lows.

33:15.518 --> 33:16.520
That's David's point.

33:17.181 --> 33:19.023
We need to practice presence with God.

33:19.043 --> 33:20.505
That's the secret to loving him more.

33:20.806 --> 33:29.778
But here's the thing, when we don't do it, that's why so many Christians, they're full of board belief and casual kinds of living.

33:31.106 --> 33:33.930
And thus they fall prey to other desires instead.

33:36.193 --> 33:37.374
You hear me out there, Christian?

33:39.637 --> 33:57.640
If you're settling for less than a life that God has come to give you, if you're just stamping the Christian membership card, submitting your monthly dues, attending church twice a month, and cashing in 2% of your tithe, occasionally coming to Bible study because you feel guilty that you haven't been in several weeks.

33:57.680 --> 33:58.962
When you do that,

33:59.970 --> 34:04.475
You're not setting yourself up for the kind of life that Christ has come to give, because He didn't come to give you that.

34:05.056 --> 34:06.278
He's come to give you so much more.

34:06.298 --> 34:12.465
I think He came from heaven to earth, lived perfectly, endured every temptation.

34:12.525 --> 34:18.713
You do die the most miserable of deaths, yet rose forth in victory over it all.

34:20.194 --> 34:24.420
Just so you could feel, man, how about all of this?

34:25.921 --> 34:26.482
No.

34:27.266 --> 34:31.874
It's deeper and richer and bigger and more beautiful than so many of us experience.

34:32.475 --> 34:38.085
And yet when we don't, when we settle for less, what happens is we fall prey to other desires.

34:39.368 --> 34:40.890
That's what happened to us from the beginning.

34:41.611 --> 34:45.659
Genesis 3, 6 says, so when the woman saw that the tree was good for food and that it was what?

34:47.141 --> 34:50.628
A delight to the eyes and that the tree was to be what?

34:51.349 --> 34:52.050
Desired.

34:52.130 --> 34:57.478
to make one wise, she took of its fruit and she ate, and she also gave some to her husband who was with her, and he ate.

34:57.498 --> 35:02.486
You see, if you delight in God, you'll desire God, but if you don't delight in God, you're going to desire something else.

35:03.488 --> 35:04.930
So what are you desiring after?

35:04.970 --> 35:14.385
And the reason you do is because you think that's gonna make you happy, but here's the thing, and how it all ties back to anger, because anger is what it is a response to someone threatening your happiness.

35:16.068 --> 35:20.114
If you don't desire him, you're threatening yourself.

35:21.250 --> 35:24.353
you're choosing to put your own happiness on the chopping block.

35:24.674 --> 35:27.376
And what you'll feel is not anger at the world.

35:27.637 --> 35:29.238
You'll feel anger at yourself.

35:31.220 --> 35:32.802
And some of you know this so very well.

35:32.882 --> 35:36.186
Like people, some of you here, you delight and love.

35:36.506 --> 35:37.908
Oh, the concept of it.

35:38.008 --> 35:40.670
And so you just desire a boyfriend or a girlfriend.

35:43.153 --> 35:47.858
But you're willing to do things that you absolutely and utterly regret.

35:48.610 --> 35:53.955
because that's what's required to be with whomever it is you've chosen to spend your time with.

35:53.975 --> 36:05.847
Some of you, you delight in success so much so that you've got a high-powered job, but you hate yourself because you have sold your soul in order to achieve it.

36:07.248 --> 36:09.851
Others of you, you delight in a particular outcome.

36:09.871 --> 36:10.832
You've got a plan for your life.

36:12.493 --> 36:17.458
And so you desire control, but not a single one of us has absolute

36:17.858 --> 36:18.819
control of anything.

36:19.900 --> 36:25.906
And so because you don't, you're stressed, you're anxious, and you're not as happy as you could be in God.

36:26.547 --> 36:28.389
That's the thing, and I need you to hear me.

36:31.212 --> 36:35.116
Delight in God is the key to a happy life.

36:37.118 --> 36:39.641
And that's not some prosperity nonsense I'm selling up here.

36:40.602 --> 36:41.243
That's the truth.

36:42.184 --> 36:44.466
There is no joy, let the joy of the Lord

36:45.282 --> 36:47.104
Psalm 16, 11, I'm gonna rattle these at you.

36:47.124 --> 36:52.972
It says, you make known to me the path of life in your presence is fullness of joy and your right hand pleasures forevermore.

36:53.032 --> 36:56.597
Psalm 63, because your steadfast love is better than life.

36:56.737 --> 36:58.559
That's a big, my lips will praise you.

36:58.619 --> 37:01.122
Psalm 84, two, my soul longs.

37:01.163 --> 37:04.206
Yes, it faints for the court to the Lord, my heart and my flesh.

37:04.427 --> 37:07.991
They sing for what for joy to the living God.

37:08.031 --> 37:13.138
And then Psalm 73, a personal favorite says this, whom have I in heaven but you God?

37:13.634 --> 37:15.916
There's nothing on earth that I desire beside you.

37:16.657 --> 37:21.082
My flesh and my heart, they may fail, but God, you're the strength of my heart and my portion forever.

37:21.282 --> 37:24.465
For behold, those who are far from you shall perish.

37:25.406 --> 37:31.772
You put an end to everyone who is unfaithful to you, but for me, it's good to be near God.

37:33.054 --> 37:36.617
It's good to be near God, so learn the discipline of presence.

37:36.637 --> 37:37.418
We gotta keep going.

37:37.799 --> 37:38.579
Look at verse five.

37:39.260 --> 37:41.202
It says this, commit your way to the Lord.

37:41.410 --> 37:42.652
Trust in him and he will act.

37:42.672 --> 37:47.318
He will bring forth your righteousness as the light and your justice as the noon day.

37:47.378 --> 37:52.105
For the sake of time, we're not going to read all the way through this Psalm.

37:52.185 --> 37:55.210
It's too big to do so, but we are going to look at this first section.

